clusters.neutral_headline: Man charged after homemade bomb allegedly thrown into crowd at Perth protest

items.title: Man charged after homemade bomb allegedly thrown into crowd at Perth protest
items.standfirst: Preliminary forensic testing indicated the device did contain explosives, WA Police Commissioner Col Blanch said.
items.content: A man has been charged after a homemade bomb was allegedly thrown into the crowd of an Invasion Day rally in Perth yesterday.A crowd of 2500 protesters were evacuated about 12.30pm yesterday after a device was thrown into the crowd on Forrest Place in the CBD.A 31-year-old man from Warwick, in Perth's northern suburbs, was taken into custody at the scene, where he allegedly told police the device may contain explosives.READ MORE: Donald Trump pulls top Border Patrol commander, other agents out of MinneapolisThe device did not detonate and no injuries were reported. Police have today confirmed the homemade improvised explosive device contained a mixture of volatile and potentially explosive chemicals, with nails and metal ball bearings affixed to the exterior."We will allege that that devIce was designed to explode upon impact, but for reasons not yet known, it didn't," WA Police Commissioner Col Blanch told radio station 6PR this morning.Police raided a home in Warwick yesterday where they allegedly found chemicals and materials commonly used to make homemade explosives.The 31-year-old man was today charged with making or possesssing explosives under suspcious cirumstances and one count of an unlawful act or omission with intent to harm.He was refused bail to appear before Perth Magistrates Court today. clusters.title: Major winter storm kills dozens of people across the US
clusters.neutral_headline: Major winter storm kills dozens of people across the US

items.title: Major winter storm kills dozens of people across the US
items.standfirst: Almost 200 million Americans are under cold weather alerts as snow, sleet and freezing rain affects swathes of the country from Texas to New England, with temperatures set to fall dangerously low this week.
items.content: Almost 200 million Americans are under cold weather alerts as snow, sleet and freezing rain affects swathes of the country from Texas to New England, with temperatures set to fall dangerously low this week.
